<p>That&#8217;s my hope, too! This kind of work is part of what I&#8217;m talking about when <a href="http://maybemaimed.com/2009/09/14/freeing-sexuality-information/" rel="nofollow">I discuss how important it is to &#8220;free sexuality information&#8221; and make it available</a> to everyone regardless of socioeconomic class or other characteristics.</p>
<blockquote><p>you are very eloquent about it, way more so than I could hope to be.</p></blockquote>
<p>Maybe I am today, but I&#8217;ve also been thinking about this for months. You spoke more eloquently about GSAs than I ever could, so I&#8217;m really grateful that you came to KFADC and brought shared your experiences around that subject with the people there.</p>
<p>@<a href="#comment-24323" rel="nofollow">Courtney</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p>I plan to transcribe the video for my housemate who is hearing impaired.</p></blockquote>
<p>That&#8217;s awesome! If it helps, you&#8217;re welcome to use the <a href="/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/Sexual%20Adultism.txt" rel="nofollow">text-only version of my presentation</a> that I put together as a starting point.</p>
<blockquote><p>May I have your permission to upload it to overstream so that I can post the video with captions instead of just a separate transcript?</p></blockquote>
<p>Yes! Absolutely! The presentation is CC-BY-NC-ND licensed, which means that you are welcome to share it in any way that you like provided you do not alter, commercialize, or re-appropriate the content. When you post it elsewhere, I&#8217;ll consider a link back to this page as sufficient attribution.</p>
<p>Thanks so much for spreading the message and for making it more accessible to hearing impaired people, <a href="#comment-24323" rel="nofollow">Courtney</a>!</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
