	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong>Trophy53</strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>20 Feb 2010</strong> at <a href="#comment-30365">09:42</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/42691c4d8c57932551aece6323165d43?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>In a world where international affairs, global economic crises, terrorism, and natural disasters abound, it is so easy to consider issues of human freedoms and dignity as secondary, let alone the consideration of youth. Yet, ideas like those you illuminated will ultimately those which will provide the wisdom and strength to resolve most if not all those issues which humanity faces, and will continue to face. Humanity must promote developing a solid framework in which people of all ages, especially young people, live without fear and restriction, without a constant need to hold their potential back. Life which celebrates diversity of expressions, tendencies, and standards. Life of openness, acceptance and respect to the unknown. Radicalism is very relative. What may seem radical now is going to be the cornerstone of future standards, and will enable what may seem now unthinkable radicalism in the future. That is a good thing, if humanity is to progress on a positive path. You are ahead of your time, but not a moment too soon.</p>
<p>I am praying that your vision will materialize sooner than later.</p>
