	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong>Isil</strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>02 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-220600">12:06</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f999b92e3a131fa252112981831c8ece?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>It is quite astonishing &#8211; each time I&#8217;m researching something close to my current thoughts and dealing with issues related to BDSM and sexuality, I end up here on your blog. Let me once again say how valuable you are, just by being a beacon out there.</p>
<p>Today I was accused of being some perverted pedophile hunting online for teens simply because I wanted to discuss writing positively about a variety of issues teenagers may have in relation to BDSM, relationships with adults (and to absolutely clarify this, I was very clearly talking about teenagers past the age of consent, which happens to be less than 18 in various European states, e.g. 15 in France and 16 in most of the rest of Europe including the UK) and (of course not positively, but realistically instead) about the current surge of gangrape and teen pregnancies in various parts of Europe. </p>
<p>Unfortunately I did so on a US American forum, and as already said got immediately declared a perverted pedophile. I was talking about writing and fiction and informative books for youths (hell, I wished I had had access to such as a teen). The topic was okay as long as everything named was understood to be depicted being negative, of course including negative consequences, sort of &#8220;see, lesson learned is don&#8217;t even think of it!&#8221; This is quite frightening. </p>
<p>What I am now interested in: does anyone know of books aimed at teenagers which are positive about BDSM, and positive about the sexual self-determination of teenagers?</p>
